    Examples

    Examples

    examples.Rmd

    The following article is an example of how easy it is to work with the data package and produce new insights using the data package.

    # install.packages("devtools")
# devtools::install_github("openwashdata/wasteskipsblantyre")
library(wasteskipsblantyre)
library(tidyverse)
library(sf)
library(tmap)
library(here)
library(httr)

    Background

    Malawi is a eastern sub-Saharan state. For this article the area of the city of Blantyre has been explored as depicted in @fig-boundaries-blantyre.

    The city is divided in 23 traditional authorities. This article will use these areas to explore and emphasize on the data contained in the wasteskipsblantyre package. The data set stores the locations of publicly accessible waste skips in Blantyre (@fig-locations) and was collected in 2021.

    In addition, data from the 2018 Malawi Census population data set shared by National Statistical Office is used for some demographic analysis.

    Hypothesis

    In the context of this fictional article we define a hypothesis:

    The number of waste skips within an traditional authorities correlates with the area of each authority.

    Analysis

    First, we have a separate look into the the the waste skips data and the data from the 2018 census for each traditional authority within Blantyre which are also called wards. After that we compare the the two data sets and look for possible correlations.

    Waste skips data

    The location of 53 public waste skips has been determined. In @fig-count-ta it is visible that number of waste skips in a traditional authority vary between 0 and 4. In average, there are 2.2 waste skips in a traditional authority.

    Number of waste skips in each traditional authority.

    The city center is located to the west of the city. In @fig-map-count a slight difference between the western and the north-eastern wards can be recognized. Nevertheless, it is very difficult to see any tendencies with regard to geographical location of the waste skips.

    Population data

    In 2018, Blantyre Cityâ€™s population was 8.00264^{5}. The population for each ward can be seen the following @fig-barplot-pop

    Population per ward.

    Since the areas of the wards differ, we will have a look into the population density of the wards in @fig-barplot-density.

    Population density per ward.

    Comparison

    In order to cross check the data and validate the hypothesis the data sets are linked together and visualized in the following figures.

    @fig-count-pop doesnâ€™t really show a correlation between the number of waste skips and the population of the wards. Nevertheless, the four most populated wards have more than 3 waste skips.

    Ward population, coloured by the number of waste skips within the ward.

    Also the population density appears to not have an influence on the placement of a waste skip as seen in @fig-count-density. It is interesting to see that the Ndirande Makata Ward and the Ndirande Gamulani Ward do not have a waste skip even though they are the 3rd and 4th most densely populated areas of the city.

    Ward population density, coloured by the number of waste skips within the ward.

    Discussion

    Short discussion about the analysis..

    Conclusion

    Unfortunately, the hypothesis could not be verified. There is no correlation between the location of waste skips and the population of the wards of Blantyre.

    We hope you enjoyed this fictional article!!
